05272nam a22006735i 9783866537026DE-B159720211129102213.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211129t20092008gw     fo  d z      eng d  a97838665370267 a10.1515/97838665370262doi  a(DE-B1597)36803  a(OCoLC)979884621  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aKJE2101b.B84 2008eb 7aLAW0510002bisacsh04a343.4/0811222  aPS 37302rvk0(DE-625)rvk/139785:1 aBueno Diaz, Odavia, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aFranchising in European Contract Law :bA comparison between the main obligations of the contracting parties in the Principles of European Law on Commercial Agency, Franchise and Distribution Contracts (PEL CAFDC), French and Spanish law /cOdavia Bueno Diaz. 1aMunich : bOtto Schmidt/De Gruyter european law publishers, c[2009] 4c©2008  a1 online resource (292 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSchriften zur Europäischen Rechtswissenschaft / European Legal Studies / Etudes juridiques européenes ,x1861-454X ;v800tFrontmatter -- tTable of Contents -- tChapter I. General Introduction -- tChapter II. Main Characteristics of the French and Spanish Law on Franchising -- tChapter III. Description and Comparison of the main Obligations of the Parties in Franchising Contracts in the PEL CAFDC, French and Spanish Law -- tChapter IV. General Conclusions -- tSummary -- tSamenvating -- tBackmatter0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe Principles of European Law on Commercial Agency, Franchise and Distribution Contracts (PEL CAFDC, 2006) are an academic proposal of the Study Group on a European Civil Code for the European-wide regulation of the contents of these three types of agreements. The academic analysis "Franchising in European Contract Law" focuses on the harmonised Principles on Franchising.At present all member states of the EU have their own regulation on franchising. This situation might change in the light of the political process of Europeanization of contract law that was initiated by the European Commission in 2001. As a result of that process the Principles on Franchising could be declared a set of rules which might be opted for by the parties to franchising contracts Europe-wide to govern their relationship. In this analysis the main obligations in franchising in PEL CAFDC are compared with those under French and Spanish law.The main conclusion of this thesis research has been that the main obligations of parties in franchising under the PEL CAFDC resemble those under French and Spanish law. Eventually, differences will arise depending on how national courts weigh the interests of the parties in each case. A second conclusion has been that a choice for the PEL CAFDC instead of for French and Spanish law could be considered a rational alternative concerning the applicable system of remedies and legal certainty.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aConflict of lawsxCommercial agents. 0aFranchises (Retail trade)xLaw and legislationzEuropean Union countries. 0aFranchises (Retail trade)xLaw and legislationzFrance. 0aFranchises (Retail trade)xLaw and legislationzSpain. 7aLAW / International.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist Complete English Language 2000-2014 PART1z978311023857008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Backlist History 2000-2014 (EN)z978311062100608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDGBA Law - 2000 - 2014z9783110636208oZDB-23-GLA08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK GESAMTPAKET / COMPLETE PACKAGE 2009z9783110219517oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertE-BOOK PACKAGE ENGLISH LANGUAGES TITLES 2009z9783110219524